WEBVTT

00:01.042 --> 00:05.500
This film was restored by StudioCanal
and the Cinémathéque Francaise

00:05.583 --> 00:09.708
with the support of
the Franco-American Cultural Fund.

00:09.792 --> 00:13.000
Pierrot le fou was shot in Techniscope,
on Eastmancolor emulsion.

00:13.083 --> 00:17.417
Techniscope was often used at the time, notably for reasons of economy,
because the image only took up two perforations per photogramme.

00:17.500 --> 00:22.000
The dupe-positive, also printed Techniscope, is lost. As for the
internegative, it had become unusable and was destroyed in 1990.

00:22.083 --> 00:26.000
A new internegative element was made on reversible film stock, with an
anamorphic image on four frames, which is still used to make prints today.

00:26.083 --> 00:30.458
However, this element doesn't reflect the qualities of the
original work, particularly in terms of the colormetrics.

00:30.542 --> 00:34.542
The restoration resides entirely in the making of a new
negative from the digitisation in 2K of the camera negative,

00:34.625 --> 00:37.000
which has the original colors of Eastmancolor.

00:37.083 --> 00:41.667
As for the sound, the original magnetic elements disappeared,
a new negative was made from a positive of the period,

00:41.750 --> 00:44.458
respecting the original mono format.

01:39.500 --> 01:44.500
<i>"Past the age of 50, Velézquez
stopped painting definite things.</i>

01:44.667 --> 01:48.583
<i>He glided round objects
with the air, with the dusk.</i>

01:48.750 --> 01:53.583
<i>He elicited quivering colours from the
shadowy transparency of the background</i>

01:53.750 --> 01:58.375
<i>and made them the invisible centre
of his silent symphony.</i>

01:58.542 --> 02:02.542
<i>He gleaned from the world
only those mysterious exchanges</i>

02:02.708 --> 02:06.167
<i>which allow shapes and sounds to intermingle</i>

02:06.333 --> 02:08.625
<i>in a secret and continuous progression</i>

02:08.792 --> 02:14.417
<i>that no collision, no involuntary
movement can halt or betray.</i>

02:14.625 --> 02:16.000
<i>Space reigns.</i>

02:17.208 --> 02:20.458
<i>It is like an airy Wave gliding over surfaces,</i>

02:20.625 --> 02:25.208
<i>absorbing their visible emanations
to define and model them.</i>

02:25.375 --> 02:30.625
<i>It carries them along like a scent, like an echo,</i>

02:30.792 --> 02:35.083
<i>and scatters them everywhere
like some imponderable dust.</i>

02:35.250 --> 02:38.667
The world he lived in was sad.

02:38.833 --> 02:42.500
The king was a degenerate,
his children were sickly,

02:42.667 --> 02:46.625
and he was surrounded by idiots,
dwarves and invalids.

02:46.792 --> 02:50.083
There were ugly clowns, dressed like princes,

02:50.250 --> 02:52.958
whose purpose was to make fun of themselves

02:53.125 --> 02:56.417
to amuse people living outside reality,

02:56.583 --> 03:01.125
who were constrained by etiquette,
who plotted and lied,

03:01.292 --> 03:05.167
who were bound
by the confessional and by remorse,

03:05.333 --> 03:09.458
with the Inquisition and silence at the door."

03:12.250 --> 03:14.250
Listen to this, little girl.

03:16.917 --> 03:19.000
"There is a sense of nostalgia,

03:19.167 --> 03:23.250
but he avoids what is ugly, sad or cruelly morbid

03:23.417 --> 03:26.542
about this oppressed childhood.

03:28.000 --> 03:34.958
Velézquez is the painter of the night,
of vast expanses and of silence,

03:35.125 --> 03:39.958
even when he paints by day,
even when he paints inside a room,

03:40.125 --> 03:44.750
even when the sounds of war,
or of the hunt, are all around him.

03:44.917 --> 03:50.333
As they didn't go out during the day,
when the sun obliterates everything,

03:50.500 --> 03:54.750
Spanish painters communed with twilight."

03:54.917 --> 03:59.375
- Isn't that beautiful?
- You're mad to read such things to them.

03:59.542 --> 04:02.583
Go on, go to bed.

04:02.750 --> 04:07.458
- Why hasn't Odile put them to bed yet?
- Because you allowed her

04:07.625 --> 04:11.708
to go to the cinema for the third time this week.

04:11.875 --> 04:14.375
To go to the cinema for the third time.

04:14.542 --> 04:18.875
They're showingJohnny Guitar.
It's an education for her.

04:19.042 --> 04:22.542
- This world is too full of fools.
- Come on, hurry.

04:22.708 --> 04:26.917
- Frank and Paola will be here soon.
- I'm not going.

04:27.083 --> 04:29.917
- I'll stay with the children.
- Don't do that.

04:30.083 --> 04:35.167
Frank is bringing his niece.
She'll look after them until we get back.

04:35.333 --> 04:38.167
She's a student. She always does this.

04:38.333 --> 04:42.042
Since when does he have a niece?
She must be a call girl.

04:42.208 --> 04:47.083
- I'm not going.
- You'll do as you're told.

04:47.250 --> 04:51.792
The head of Standard Oil will be there,
and Daddy will introduce you.

04:51.958 --> 04:55.000
I should sue the TV station for firing me.

04:55.167 --> 04:58.500
Oh, no, you won't. You'd lose the court case.

04:58.667 --> 05:02.917
And when they offer you a job, please accept it.

05:03.083 --> 05:05.667
Come, that's enough.

05:10.125 --> 05:17.000
- Aren't you wearing a slip?
- I'm wearing an invisible girdle.

05:17.167 --> 05:22.583
"Under my new trousers, Scandal,
for a youthful figure."

05:22.750 --> 05:27.083
<i>We've had Athenian civilisation,
we've had the Renaissance,</i>

05:27.250 --> 05:30.667
<i>and now our civilisation centres round the arse.</i>

05:30.833 --> 05:34.417
- Follow me, I'll show you round.
- She loves children.

05:34.583 --> 05:38.000
If there's a problem, you can call us on...

05:38.167 --> 05:40.375
225-7001.

05:40.542 --> 05:43.667
- This is Frank's niece.
- Yes?

05:45.042 --> 05:47.125
Good evening.

05:49.708 --> 05:51.083
Hi.

05:51.250 --> 05:56.292
225. Haven't you read Balzac?
How about César Birotteau

05:56.500 --> 05:59.500
and the 5th Symphony resounding in his head?

05:59.667 --> 06:02.833
- What's up with you?
- Come on, let's go.

06:03.000 --> 06:06.708
<i>Chapter two: a surprise party
given by Mr and Mrs Expresso,</i>

06:06.875 --> 06:08.500
<i>whose daughter is my wife.</i>

06:08.667 --> 06:14.167
An Alfa Romeo has great acceleration,
powerful disc brakes,

06:14.333 --> 06:20.000
holds the road perfectly
and is an exceptional touring car.

06:20.167 --> 06:25.458
It is safe, fast, pleasant to drive,
responsive and stable.

06:27.250 --> 06:32.833
It's easy to look fresh. Soap cleanses,
cologne refreshes and scent perfumes.

06:33.000 --> 06:39.333
And to avoid perspiration, I use Printil,
and feel fresh for the rest of the day.

06:39.500 --> 06:45.417
Printil is available as a stick
deodorant, a roll-on or a spray.

06:45.583 --> 06:48.833
But the Oldsmobile Rocket 88 is even better.

06:49.000 --> 06:52.042
Look at its rigorous design.

06:52.208 --> 06:54.417
Its powerful, sober lines

06:54.583 --> 07:00.292
show that elegance and
exceptional performance can be combined.

07:02.833 --> 07:05.333
You look lonely.

07:09.958 --> 07:13.792
He's American. He doesn't speak French.

07:13.958 --> 07:18.583
What's his name? What does he do?

07:26.417 --> 07:30.875
He's Samuel Fuller.
He's an American film director.

07:31.042 --> 07:35.708
- He's makingLes <i>Fleurs du</i> Mal.
- Baudelaire, that's good.

07:38.875 --> 07:43.250
I've always wanted to know
what cinema is, exactly.

07:52.333 --> 07:54.833
Films are like battlegrounds.

07:57.125 --> 07:59.208
Love.

07:59.292 --> 08:02.125
Hate.

08:02.208 --> 08:04.250
Action.

08:04.333 --> 08:06.292
Violence.

08:06.375 --> 08:09.333
And death.

08:09.500 --> 08:12.375
In one word, emotions.

08:21.042 --> 08:27.833
My hairdo has stayed in place
all day thanks to Elnett Satin.

08:28.000 --> 08:35.167
And I can brush the hairspray off
just as easily as I sprayed it on.

08:38.250 --> 08:42.208
My hair is like golden silk.

08:43.542 --> 08:47.625
It's shiny and clean.

08:47.792 --> 08:53.625
Women should renounce flimsy negligees
and romantic nightgowns.

08:55.250 --> 09:01.167
In daylight, lingerie loses its charm
and can look indecent.

09:06.917 --> 09:09.542
<i>Tristesse d'Olympio.</i>

09:13.875 --> 09:17.625
- Give me the keys to the car.
- Aren't you staying?

09:17.792 --> 09:19.875
No, I'm tired.

09:21.292 --> 09:24.833
I have a seeing system, called "eyes".

09:25.000 --> 09:30.208
I use my ears to hear and my mouth to speak.

09:30.375 --> 09:35.875
I feel as if these systems
were separate. There's no unity.

09:36.042 --> 09:39.292
We should all feel unique,

09:39.458 --> 09:42.583
but I feel as if I were many people.

09:43.667 --> 09:45.583
You speak too much.

09:45.750 --> 09:50.375
- Having to listen to you is tiresome.
- I do speak too much.

09:50.542 --> 09:53.667
Lonely men always speak too much.

09:56.292 --> 09:59.125
I'll wait for you at home.

10:02.958 --> 10:07.958
<i>Next chapter: despair, memory, freedom,</i>

10:08.125 --> 10:13.125
<i>bitterness, hope, a search for times past.</i>

10:13.292 --> 10:15.125
<i>Marianne Renoir.</i>

10:24.208 --> 10:26.292
You're still here?

10:36.250 --> 10:38.417
Sorry.

10:38.583 --> 10:40.833
The tube is shut. How will you get back?

10:41.000 --> 10:43.083
I don't know.

10:44.583 --> 10:50.042
- Are you alone?
- Yes, I got bored, so I came back.

10:50.208 --> 10:53.875
Are you all right? You seem down.

10:54.042 --> 10:58.708
There are days when
you only seem to come across morons.

10:58.875 --> 11:03.875
It leads you to look in the mirror
and question yourself.

11:05.500 --> 11:08.083
I'll drive you home.

11:20.042 --> 11:22.417
- He lent you his car?
- Yes.

11:22.583 --> 11:25.792
- Why? Don't you like Americans?
- No, I do.

11:28.000 --> 11:34.292
- It feels strange to see you again.
- Yes, it's been four years.

11:34.458 --> 11:38.958
It's been five-and-a-half years. It was October.

11:39.125 --> 11:41.083
You've married.

11:41.250 --> 11:44.667
I met a rich Italian,
but I'm not that interested in her.

11:44.833 --> 11:49.333
- Why don't you divorce her?
- I felt like it, but I'm too lazy.

11:49.500 --> 11:56.417
You have to feel alive to want anything,
have you noticed that?

11:56.583 --> 12:02.833
- Do you still teach Spanish?
- No, I worked in TV, but I resigned.

12:04.667 --> 12:07.958
- How about you?
- Nothing special.

12:08.125 --> 12:10.917
- You don't want to talk about yourself?
- No.

12:11.083 --> 12:13.917
A friend of mine saw you in London two years ago.

12:14.083 --> 12:18.333
- Are you still seeing that American?
- That was over a long time ago.

12:18.500 --> 12:22.042
How long have you known Frank?

12:22.208 --> 12:28.083
- I... just met him by chance.
- You're as mysterious as ever.

12:28.250 --> 12:31.833
It's just that I don't like to talk about myself.

12:32.000 --> 12:35.125
All right, then I'll keep quiet.

12:42.542 --> 12:49.375
<i>His garrison had already been decimated
by the Vietcong, who also lost 115 men.</i>

12:49.542 --> 12:51.917
It's awful, so impersonal.

12:52.083 --> 12:55.667
- What is?
- They speak of 115 resistance fighters,

12:55.833 --> 12:57.875
and it means nothing.

12:58.042 --> 13:02.792
And yet, each one of them is a man,
and we know nothing about them

13:02.958 --> 13:08.500
if they love a woman, have children,
prefer the cinema to the theatre.

13:08.667 --> 13:13.792
We know nothing about them.
All we can say is: 115 dead.

13:14.000 --> 13:18.500
It's the same with photographs.
It's always fascinated me.

13:18.667 --> 13:23.167
You see the man, frozen in time,
with a caption underneath.

13:23.333 --> 13:25.875
He was either a coward or a hero.

13:26.042 --> 13:30.958
But at the time the picture was taken,
no one can say who he really was,

13:31.125 --> 13:35.917
or who he was thinking about.
His wife? His mistress?

13:36.083 --> 13:41.750
The past? The future? About basketball?
We'll never know.

13:42.833 --> 13:45.000
That's life.

13:45.167 --> 13:50.167
What upsets me is that life
is so different from novels.

13:50.333 --> 13:53.292
I wish they were the same.

13:53.458 --> 13:57.375
Clear, logical, organised.

13:58.500 --> 14:01.042
But they aren't.

14:01.208 --> 14:04.667
They're more similar than people think.

14:04.833 --> 14:07.417
No, they're not, Pierrot.

14:07.583 --> 14:10.375
Must I remind you to call me Ferdinand?

14:10.542 --> 14:14.708
But one can't say: "My friend, Ferdinand."

14:14.875 --> 14:18.542
Yes, you can. Just try it, Marianne.

14:20.083 --> 14:22.500
I'll try.

14:22.667 --> 14:25.583
I'll do anything you want.

14:26.917 --> 14:29.833
So will I, Marianne.

14:31.792 --> 14:35.458
I'm putting my hand on your knee.

14:35.625 --> 14:38.167
Me too, Marianne.

14:40.750 --> 14:43.875
I'm kissing you everywhere.

14:45.125 --> 14:47.208
Me too, Marianne.

14:59.333 --> 15:01.250
We'll see.

15:01.417 --> 15:04.208
<i>Marianne Renoir.</i>

15:19.417 --> 15:22.125
Come on, wake up!

16:00.833 --> 16:02.792
- I was right.
- About what?

16:02.958 --> 16:06.917
You didn't believe me when I said
we'd always love each other.

16:07.083 --> 16:10.292
I've never said I'd love you forever.

16:10.458 --> 16:12.875
Oh, my love

16:13.042 --> 16:17.542
You never promised to adore me at all

16:19.500 --> 16:22.750
We've never exchanged such vows

16:22.917 --> 16:26.333
Though we know each other so well

16:27.875 --> 16:31.583
We'd never have believed
we'd forever be slaves to love

16:31.708 --> 16:34.833
As we're both so fickle

16:35.042 --> 16:43.250
And yet, without having to say a word,
little by little

16:45.167 --> 16:50.708
Feelings slipped between our bodies,
which so loved to merge

16:52.667 --> 16:58.708
And then words of love fell
from our naked lips, little by little

17:00.333 --> 17:07.292
Many words of love mingled with our kisses

17:11.583 --> 17:15.292
I never would have believed
I would always love you

17:15.458 --> 17:18.000
My love

17:18.167 --> 17:23.375
We never thought we could live together
without tiring of each other

17:24.667 --> 17:31.833
Or that we'd wake up every morning
so happy to be in the same bed

17:33.333 --> 17:40.458
Or wish for no more than the simple
joy of being so comfortable together

17:55.792 --> 18:03.500
And yet, without either of us
saying much, little by little

18:06.000 --> 18:11.792
Our feelings have bound us together forever

18:14.000 --> 18:20.750
Feelings which were stronger
than any known or unknown words of love

18:20.917 --> 18:27.167
Feelings which were more passionate
than either of us could have anticipated

18:27.333 --> 18:32.333
Don't ever promise to adore me forever

18:33.583 --> 18:39.458
Let us not exchange such promises,
given the way we both are

18:40.958 --> 18:45.833
Let us pretend that our love

18:46.042 --> 18:50.583
is a love without a future

18:50.750 --> 18:55.583
We'll know by the time we're dead
if we carried on loving each other.

18:55.750 --> 19:00.250
I know that I love you.
It's you I'm not so sure about.

19:00.417 --> 19:04.083
- I'm not sure.
- I do love you, Marianne. I do.

19:04.250 --> 19:06.833
Well, we'll see.

19:09.000 --> 19:13.167
- <i>Your wife</i> came <i>round this morning.</i>
- <i>Who cares?</i>

19:13.333 --> 19:17.667
<i>- That's not all.
- I just told you I don't care.</i>

19:17.833 --> 19:20.458
<i>Marianne told Ferdinand a complicated story.</i>

19:20.625 --> 19:23.833
<i>- I met some people...
- It was like the Algerian war.</i>

19:24.000 --> 19:28.708
<i>- I'll explain everything.
- It was like waking from a bad dream.</i>

20:18.125 --> 20:20.375
<i>- Frank had your keys?
- I'll explain.</i>

20:20.542 --> 20:23.667
<i>Were you in love with him? Did he ever kiss you?</i>

20:23.833 --> 20:26.417
<i>I'll explain everything.</i>

21:18.958 --> 21:23.750
<i>- It was a complicated story.
- To wake from a bad dream.</i>

21:23.917 --> 21:26.500
<i>- Politics.
- An organisation.</i>

21:26.667 --> 21:29.417
<i>Arms traffic.</i>

21:29.583 --> 21:32.167
<i>Silently, silently.</i>

21:34.375 --> 21:35.875
<i>Silently.</i>

21:49.000 --> 21:51.333
<i>- It's me, Marianne.
- Did he kiss you?</i>

21:51.500 --> 21:55.083
<i>- A complicated story.
- Were you in love with him?</i>

21:55.250 --> 21:58.292
<i>- Used my apartment.
- It was like the Algerian war.</i>

21:58.458 --> 22:01.208
<i>- I have a brother.
- To wake from a bad dream.</i>

22:01.375 --> 22:04.500
<i>We had to leave quickly.</i>

22:04.667 --> 22:06.833
<i>- To knock out. Garage.
- Who is he?</i>

22:07.000 --> 22:10.542
<i>To go south. No money.</i>

22:10.708 --> 22:14.000
<i>It was high time we left this rotten world.</i>

22:14.167 --> 22:18.542
<i>- We left Paris by a unique route.
- Recognising two of her own,</i>

22:18.708 --> 22:22.208
<i>the Statue of Liberty greeted us warmly.</i>

22:24.625 --> 22:26.167
Sir!

22:28.583 --> 22:31.542
- Put a tiger in my engine.
- We don't sell tigers here.

22:31.708 --> 22:34.833
Then fill her up and keep quiet.

22:52.000 --> 22:55.125
He'll be less suspicious if it's me.

23:05.458 --> 23:07.958
That'll be 4,900.

23:08.125 --> 23:11.250
Check the water and the oil, my man.

23:19.833 --> 23:22.417
Help me, you fool.

23:29.375 --> 23:34.375
- Shit, there's another one.
- Get in the car.

23:35.333 --> 23:38.708
- Don't you have any money?
- No, sir, we don't.

23:38.875 --> 23:41.500
Don't you want to work to earn money?

23:41.667 --> 23:46.958
- No, sir, we don't.
- So how will you pay for the petrol?

23:48.750 --> 23:51.875
Shit, there's another one. Stay there.

24:09.917 --> 24:12.125
I'll call the police!

24:14.875 --> 24:17.000
<i>- Total.
- It was an adventure film.</i>

24:17.167 --> 24:19.250
<i>- A diadem of blood.
- Total.</i>

24:19.417 --> 24:21.958
- Tender is the Night.
- <i>A</i> romantic novel.

24:22.125 --> 24:26.625
- <i>A</i> romantic novel.
- Tender is the Night.

24:27.958 --> 24:31.083
We'll find my brother eventually.

24:38.583 --> 24:44.500
- What does he deal in, exactly?
- Stuff in Africa.

24:44.667 --> 24:47.375
In Angola, in the Congo.

24:47.542 --> 24:50.125
I thought he worked for Télé Monte Carlo.

24:50.292 --> 24:51.833
Yes, that too.

24:56.375 --> 24:59.292
So, where are we going?

25:00.750 --> 25:05.375
We said we'd go to Nice.
And then, maybe, on to Italy.

25:05.542 --> 25:10.750
12,000 francs won't last us to Nice.
We'd better abandon this car.

25:13.708 --> 25:17.750
- Have you ever killed a man, Pierrot?
- My name is Ferdinand.

25:17.958 --> 25:20.542
Why do you ask?

25:22.042 --> 25:25.667
Because you won't like it.

25:26.958 --> 25:30.750
I wonder what she told the police.

25:30.917 --> 25:34.833
- Maybe they've not questioned her yet.
- Don't you believe it.

25:35.000 --> 25:38.208
She must have really slammed you.

25:38.375 --> 25:42.167
She's quite right. I'm sorry for her.

25:42.333 --> 25:47.042
Sorry? Men like you are always sorry.

25:48.500 --> 25:51.083
And always too late.

26:10.375 --> 26:13.292
- What are you doing?
- I'm looking at myself.

26:13.458 --> 26:15.042
And what do you see?

26:15.250 --> 26:20.458
The face of a man who's going to
throw himself off a cliff at high speed.

26:21.833 --> 26:28.375
I see a woman who is in love with the
man who'll throw himself off a cliff.

26:28.542 --> 26:31.125
So let's kiss.

26:39.958 --> 26:45.458
<i>- The following day.
- We got back into the car.</i>

26:45.625 --> 26:50.167
<i>- And arrived in a little town.
- We're almost out of petrol.</i>

26:50.333 --> 26:52.625
<i>Marianne and Ferdinand stop at a bar.</i>

26:52.792 --> 26:56.208
<i>They order something
and wonder how they'll pay for it.</i>

26:56.375 --> 27:00.875
<i>- The police are after them.
- They're getting odd looks from people.</i>

27:01.083 --> 27:03.667
<i>- The police...
- People...</i>

27:03.833 --> 27:06.792
<i>- They're getting odd looks from people.
- There's...</i>

27:06.958 --> 27:09.458
Laszlo Kovacs, student.

27:09.625 --> 27:16.125
Born on the 25th January 1936, in Santo Domingo.

27:16.292 --> 27:19.167
I left after the American landing.

27:19.333 --> 27:23.583
I came to France as a political refugee.

27:23.750 --> 27:28.208
France is the country of freedom,
equality and brotherhood.

27:28.375 --> 27:32.708
Viviane Blassel, born on
the 21st March 1943 in Marseille.

27:32.875 --> 27:36.958
I'm 22. I work at the cosmetics counter
in a department store in Auxerre.

27:37.125 --> 27:43.125
Eté André, born on the 25th May 1903
in Marbouie, Eure-et-Loir.

27:43.292 --> 27:48.167
62 years old. Currently acting as a film extra.

27:48.333 --> 27:51.083
<i>Let's tell stories,
maybe they'll take pity on us.</i>

27:51.250 --> 27:54.667
<i>- What shall we tell them?
- About the fall of Constantinople,</i>

27:54.833 --> 27:58.250
<i>about Nicolas de Staels suicide.</i>

27:58.417 --> 28:01.833
<i>About William Wilson,
who saw his double in the street</i>

28:02.000 --> 28:03.875
<i>and went after him to kill him.</i>

28:04.042 --> 28:07.625
<i>And once he had, he realised he'd killed himself</i>

28:07.792 --> 28:09.833
<i>and his double was still alive.</i>

28:10.000 --> 28:12.583
<i>OK, they might even give us some money.</i>

28:12.750 --> 28:15.667
<i>Marianne, who had the eyes
of Aucassin and Nicolette,</i>

28:15.833 --> 28:19.250
<i>told them about William of Orange's
nephew, Vivien,</i>

28:19.417 --> 28:23.417
<i>who died fighting 30,000 Saracens.</i>

28:23.583 --> 28:28.500
<i>He bled from 1,000 wounds and he fought
alone, for he'd sworn not to retreat.</i>

28:28.667 --> 28:33.333
<i>Oh, young and gentle nephew,
why such a mad and noble oath?</i>

28:33.500 --> 28:37.042
<i>Ferdinand told them the story of Guynemer,</i>

28:37.208 --> 28:41.542
<i>but they didn't listen to him,
so he spoke of the summer,</i>

28:41.708 --> 28:46.000
<i>and of how lovers crave the warm night air.</i>

28:46.167 --> 28:50.875
<i>He spoke of man, and the seasons,
and unexpected encounters.</i>

28:51.042 --> 28:54.417
<i>But he told them never to ask which came first,</i>

28:54.583 --> 28:58.583
<i>words or things,
nor to ask what will happen next.</i>

28:58.792 --> 29:01.833
<i>I feel alive, that's all that matters.</i>

29:26.000 --> 29:28.583
I have an idea.

29:30.042 --> 29:33.167
We'll pretend we've had an accident.

29:44.417 --> 29:48.583
That way, the police will think
we're dead. OK, Pierrot?

29:48.792 --> 29:51.625
My name is Ferdinand.

29:51.792 --> 29:56.250
All we have to do is burn the car.
They'll think we've burned too.

29:56.417 --> 29:59.958
- Always fire, blood and war!
- It wasn't my idea!

30:00.125 --> 30:04.750
Bring the car closer.
It has to look real. This isn't a film.

30:06.917 --> 30:09.708
Come closer. Hurry up!

30:15.792 --> 30:21.292
- I don't have any matches. Let's go.
- It doesn't matter. Give me the rifle.

30:23.125 --> 30:27.708
- It's the make that killed Kennedy.
- Didn't you know I killed him?

30:27.875 --> 30:30.583
- Get out of the way.
- Wait a minute.

30:30.750 --> 30:33.375
- It's burning well.
- Yep.

30:33.583 --> 30:38.875
Do you know what was in the suitcase?
Dollars. The ones in the flat.

30:39.042 --> 30:43.625
- I bet you didn't warn me on purpose.
- That's right.

30:43.792 --> 30:46.792
Think what we could have done with that money.

30:46.917 --> 30:51.500
We could have gone to Chicago,
Las Vegas, Monte Carlo. You idiot!

30:51.667 --> 30:57.875
I'd have gone to Florence or Athens.
Let's go, travel broadens the mind.

31:52.833 --> 31:55.542
<i>- Chapter eight.
- A season in hell.</i>

31:55.667 --> 31:58.458
<i>- Chapter eight.
- We crossed France.</i>

31:58.625 --> 32:01.333
<i>- Like shadows.
- Like mirrors.</i>

34:07.042 --> 34:09.083
<i>- Like shadows.
- Like mirrors.</i>

34:09.250 --> 34:13.167
<i>I saw the cafe where Van Gogh
decided to cut off his ear.</i>

34:13.375 --> 34:17.750
<i>- You're a liar. What did you see?
- I saw...</i>

34:22.792 --> 34:26.458
- Look, Pierrot, a Ford Galaxy.
- My name is Ferdinand.

34:26.625 --> 34:29.708
Yes, that's the '62 model.

34:29.833 --> 34:32.750
- Show that you're a man.
- Let me finish.

34:32.917 --> 34:37.542
"After eating up a good many miles,
they came to the Bayuda desert,

34:37.708 --> 34:40.917
which they had to cross to reach Khartoum.

34:41.083 --> 34:46.833
'Not much shade!' they grumbled,
as they set out under a burning sun.

34:47.000 --> 34:50.792
'We'd be better off
in the shade of a glass of lager!"'

34:50.958 --> 34:54.167
Make up your mind or I'll hitchhike alone.

34:54.333 --> 34:56.583
All right, let's go.

35:18.167 --> 35:21.125
A grease-job.

35:21.292 --> 35:24.292
Where are the toilets?

35:24.458 --> 35:26.542
Come on, Mimi.

35:35.875 --> 35:39.042
Hey, kid! How'd you like to own a car like this?

35:39.208 --> 35:41.792
Well, you never will.

36:14.792 --> 36:17.375
Marianne, the jacket!

36:20.042 --> 36:24.167
Hey, kid! How'd you like to earn 10,000 francs?

37:07.958 --> 37:10.333
<i>The landscape rose slowly before us.</i>

37:10.500 --> 37:14.500
<i>Many centuries fled into the distance,
like storms.</i>

37:24.500 --> 37:27.625
Get rid of the clothes while I turn around.

37:35.542 --> 37:38.125
Hey! Not my comic book!

38:16.875 --> 38:19.917
- Well?
- Nothing much.

38:20.042 --> 38:25.750
They questioned her.
She said she saw us naked in my bed.

38:25.917 --> 38:28.375
You see? And you called me a liar.

38:28.542 --> 38:32.750
- Anything else?
- You're pretty interested in your wife.

38:32.917 --> 38:38.542
<i>Nothing happened.
I don't understand. He went mad.</i>

38:39.542 --> 38:43.250
As soon as you leave a woman,
she says you've gone mad.

38:43.417 --> 38:46.333
Men are exactly the same.

38:47.500 --> 38:49.083
That's true.

38:49.208 --> 38:53.458
Besides, I don't know why,
but I'm beginning to smell death.

38:53.625 --> 38:58.042
- Admit that you miss her!
- Stop, you're getting on my nerves.

38:58.208 --> 39:02.958
The smell of death in the landscape,
the trees, in women's faces, in cars...

39:03.125 --> 39:06.375
What are we going to do without money?

39:06.542 --> 39:10.167
- We can't even get to Italy.
- We can stop anywhere.

39:15.333 --> 39:19.625
- We can stop anywhere.
- What will we do all day?

39:19.792 --> 39:23.708
We must find my brother.
He'll give us lots of money.

39:23.875 --> 39:29.708
Then we'll find a smart hotel and have some fun.

39:29.833 --> 39:32.583
- She just wants to have fun.
- Who are you talking to?

39:32.750 --> 39:35.500
To the audience.

39:35.667 --> 39:39.125
I told you you were having regrets.

39:39.292 --> 39:42.500
- You were crazy to do this.
- No, I'm in love.

39:42.667 --> 39:45.667
It's the same thing.

39:45.833 --> 39:49.458
I've decided never to fall in love again.

39:49.625 --> 39:52.917
- I think it's disgusting.
- Don't say that.

40:00.958 --> 40:02.500
Don't say that.

40:02.667 --> 40:06.625
Ten minutes ago, I saw death everywhere.
And now look,

40:06.792 --> 40:10.375
the sea, the waves, the sky.

40:10.542 --> 40:13.875
Life may be sad, but it's still beautiful.

40:14.042 --> 40:17.708
I suddenly feel free. We can do
whatever we want when we want.

40:17.875 --> 40:22.458
- Right, left, right, left.
- Look at the little fool.

40:22.625 --> 40:26.875
He's driving down a straight line
and he has to follow it all the way.

40:27.042 --> 40:28.875
What? Look.

40:41.042 --> 40:43.458
<i>- Chapter eight.
- A season in hell.</i>

40:43.625 --> 40:47.833
<i>- Love needs to be reinvented.
- Real life is elsewhere.</i>

40:47.958 --> 40:52.500
<i>Many centuries fled into the distance,
like storms.</i>

40:52.667 --> 40:55.917
<i>I held her close and began to cry.</i>

40:56.083 --> 40:59.500
<i>It was the first, it was the only dream.</i>

41:17.542 --> 41:22.208
- Are you coming, then?
- Yes. Where are we going?

41:22.333 --> 41:25.125
To the mysterious island.

41:25.292 --> 41:28.208
- To do what?
- Nothing. Just exist.

41:28.375 --> 41:32.000
- That won't be any fun.
- That's life.

41:34.333 --> 41:36.917
No, not at all.

41:37.125 --> 41:41.958
It's a good thing I don't like spinach,
or I'd eat it,

41:42.125 --> 41:44.583
and I can't stand the stuff.

41:44.750 --> 41:49.417
It's the same with you, only the other way round.

41:50.917 --> 41:53.458
There was a film like that with Michel Simon.

41:53.583 --> 41:58.167
- He was taken by this girl...
- You did want to change your life.

41:58.333 --> 42:01.917
- I didn't mean to be nasty.
- You said we'd see this through.

42:02.125 --> 42:04.333
To the end of the night, yes.

42:22.208 --> 42:25.333
What a good view of the moon.

42:27.333 --> 42:32.625
- I see nothing special.
- I do. I can see a man.

42:32.792 --> 42:36.958
Maybe it's Leonov, or that American, White.

42:37.125 --> 42:39.167
Yes, I see him too.

42:39.333 --> 42:43.208
But it's neither a Rusky
nor a nephew of Uncle Sam.

42:43.375 --> 42:45.083
I'll tell you who it is.

42:45.250 --> 42:49.833
It's the moon's only inhabitant.
And do you know what he's doing?

42:50.000 --> 42:53.417
- Leaving as fast as he can.
- Why?

42:53.583 --> 42:54.958
Look.

42:55.167 --> 42:59.208
Because he's had enough.
He was glad to see Leonov turn up.

42:59.375 --> 43:04.167
Someone to talk to at last!
He'd been all alone for an eternity.

43:04.333 --> 43:08.292
But Leonov tried to brainwash him
with the complete works of Lenin.

43:08.458 --> 43:12.375
So when White landed,
he sought refuge in his camp.

43:12.542 --> 43:16.542
But he'd barely had time to say "hello",
when White emptied a Coke down him,

43:16.708 --> 43:18.583
and even expected thanks.

43:18.750 --> 43:23.792
So he's fed up. He'll leave them
to shoot it out and go.

43:23.958 --> 43:26.542
- Where will he go?
- He'll come here.

43:26.708 --> 43:31.000
Because he thinks you're beautiful.
He admires you.

43:38.458 --> 43:43.708
I find your legs and your breasts very moving.

43:48.042 --> 43:50.125
Be quiet.

44:06.667 --> 44:08.250
<i>Chapter seven.</i>

44:08.417 --> 44:11.958
<i>- A poet named revolver.
- Robert Browning.</i>

44:12.125 --> 44:14.458
<i>- Get away.
- Never.</i>

44:14.625 --> 44:17.333
<i>- As long as I'm here.
- And you're you.</i>

44:17.500 --> 44:20.542
<i>As long as the universe will hold us.</i>

44:20.708 --> 44:23.708
<i>- I, who love you.
- And you, who reject me.</i>

44:23.875 --> 44:27.417
<i>- As long as one of us wants to run.
- It's too much like fate.</i>

44:47.167 --> 44:51.125
I HAVE DECIDED TO KEEP A JOURNAL.

45:17.083 --> 45:20.000
WE LIVE BY HUNTING AND FISHING. TUESDAY: NOTHING.

45:45.958 --> 45:47.500
EYES: LANDSCAPES.

45:47.667 --> 45:52.667
MOUTH: ONOMATOPOEIA THAT BECOME LANGUAGE.

45:56.458 --> 45:59.875
THE WRITER CHOOSES TO APPEAL...
FREEDOM OF OTHERS...

46:04.917 --> 46:08.042
- Did you get my books?
- No, but I found this.

46:08.208 --> 46:10.667
- The author shares your name.
- Ferdinand.

46:10.833 --> 46:12.667
You've heard of him?

46:12.833 --> 46:17.583
"I am fire, I am light, I am a miracle.

46:17.750 --> 46:21.958
I can no longer hear. I rise.

46:22.125 --> 46:25.292
I fly through the air.

46:25.458 --> 46:28.333
It's too much.

46:28.500 --> 46:32.417
I've seen happiness before me.

46:32.583 --> 46:34.917
Supernatural emotion!

46:40.042 --> 46:44.792
And now... I know nothing.

46:47.125 --> 46:50.625
I reach out my hand,

46:52.958 --> 46:55.958
and dare, moving right,

46:57.083 --> 47:00.083
to touch, to caress,

47:00.250 --> 47:04.583
the hair of my dear fairy, of my beloved marvel,

47:04.750 --> 47:06.625
Virginia.

47:06.792 --> 47:10.917
<i>Guignol's Band</i>.Are you coming?

47:11.083 --> 47:14.125
"Perfect happiness!

47:14.292 --> 47:20.917
My ecstasy was so intense that I dared not move.

47:21.083 --> 47:26.875
Happy till I could cry, filled
with happiness, I quiver, quiver.

47:33.500 --> 47:38.500
My heart is bursting, burning me,
and I, too, have become flame.

47:38.667 --> 47:42.333
I am part of space, I cling to Virginia."

47:42.500 --> 47:45.083
Let me take your book.

47:48.375 --> 47:53.750
"You promised me China, Tibet, Mr Sosthéne,

47:53.917 --> 47:57.708
the Sunda Islands and wonderful, magical plants."

47:57.875 --> 48:00.792
Where are all these places?

48:00.958 --> 48:06.333
"Cham-cham-cham... ratatam...
I knew that he was lying."

48:09.792 --> 48:11.958
- What day is it?
- Friday.

48:12.125 --> 48:15.292
- You'll never leave me?
- Of course not.

48:15.458 --> 48:19.292
- Of course?
- Yes.

48:19.458 --> 48:21.542
Of course.

48:29.125 --> 48:31.750
Yes, of course.

48:38.417 --> 48:41.667
THURSDAY: POETRY, THE LOSER WINS.

48:43.917 --> 48:48.833
What can I do? I don't know what to do.

49:00.625 --> 49:04.042
Quiet! I'm trying to write.

49:04.208 --> 49:09.917
"This is the issue.
You wait for me, and I'm not there.

49:10.042 --> 49:16.292
I come into the room and only then
do I begin to exist for you.

49:16.458 --> 49:21.833
And yet I existed before that,
I thought, maybe I even suffered.

49:22.000 --> 49:26.667
This is the issue:
to show you, alive, thinking of me,

49:26.833 --> 49:30.583
and to see myself alive, by that very fact."

49:30.750 --> 49:33.333
I'll underline this.

49:37.792 --> 49:41.250
Are you thinking of your brother
and the whole arms business?

49:41.417 --> 49:42.792
No.

49:46.167 --> 49:49.250
Then why do you look sad?

49:49.417 --> 49:55.250
Because you speak to me with words,
and I look at you with feelings.

49:55.417 --> 49:59.583
It's impossible to have a conversation with you.

49:59.750 --> 50:02.333
You never have any ideas, just feelings.

50:02.500 --> 50:05.833
That's not true. Feelings contain ideas.

50:07.000 --> 50:10.167
Let's try to have a serious conversation.

50:10.333 --> 50:15.417
You'll tell me what you like,
what you want, and I'll do the same.

50:15.583 --> 50:17.833
Go on, you start.

50:18.000 --> 50:21.417
Flowers, animals...

50:25.000 --> 50:28.708
Blue skies, the sound of music...

50:30.083 --> 50:33.708
I don't know. Everything. And you?

50:36.042 --> 50:38.958
Ambition...

50:39.125 --> 50:41.000
Hope...

50:41.167 --> 50:45.333
Movement, accidents.

50:47.458 --> 50:50.583
What else? I don't know. Everything.

50:56.083 --> 50:59.250
You see? I was right five years ago.

51:01.833 --> 51:04.958
We don't understand each other.

51:06.708 --> 51:11.167
What can I do? I don't know what to do.

51:24.875 --> 51:31.125
SUNDAY: SHE OPENED THE... THEN...

51:31.292 --> 51:35.458
MONDAY...

51:42.542 --> 51:45.833
- How's the old man?
- Not bad.

51:46.000 --> 51:49.750
I've found an idea for a novel.

51:49.917 --> 51:53.000
I won't describe people's lives,

51:53.167 --> 51:57.750
but life itself, just life.

51:59.125 --> 52:06.417
Everything that takes place between
people: space, sounds and colours.

52:07.667 --> 52:11.292
It should be possible.

52:11.500 --> 52:14.542
Joyce tried to do it,

52:14.708 --> 52:19.083
but I should be able to improve on him.

52:19.250 --> 52:22.417
Here are your books.

52:22.583 --> 52:25.292
These aren't the ones.

52:25.458 --> 52:31.458
- One of them is missing. I said five.
- I bought myself a record.

52:31.625 --> 52:36.375
I said a record for every 50 books.
Music comes after literature.

52:36.542 --> 52:39.125
If you don't like it...

52:44.875 --> 52:49.042
My little one, it's all as one.

52:50.125 --> 52:55.958
- What's wrong with you?
- I can make rhymes, too, stupid.

52:56.083 --> 52:59.542
- What's up, Marianne?
- I've had enough!

52:59.708 --> 53:05.042
I'm sick of the sea, the sun, the sand,
tins - everything!

53:05.208 --> 53:09.875
I'm sick of wearing the same dress!
I want to leave.

53:11.583 --> 53:13.542
I want to live a full life.

53:13.708 --> 53:19.958
- What do you want me to do?
- I don't know. I'll leave.

53:20.125 --> 53:22.958
I threw away the rest of our money.

53:23.125 --> 53:26.250
- Where?
- In the sea, you fool.

53:27.500 --> 53:29.042
Here.

53:32.292 --> 53:35.167
You're mad, Marianne.

53:35.333 --> 53:38.458
If we're to leave, we'll need money.

53:43.333 --> 53:48.042
There are loads of tourists. We can rob them.

53:48.167 --> 53:52.875
- Come on, Pierrot!
- My name is Ferdinand.

53:53.042 --> 53:56.500
Let's stop pretending to be
in a book by Jules Verne.

53:56.667 --> 54:03.667
Let's go back to our thriller -
full of cars, guns and nightclubs.

54:03.792 --> 54:06.083
Come on!

54:06.250 --> 54:09.167
Wait for me, Marianne!

54:11.375 --> 54:16.375
- Does your brother really exist?
- You never believe me.

54:26.500 --> 54:30.958
Say, if we find Fred and he gives us some money,

54:31.125 --> 54:34.250
can't we go to Miami?

54:36.708 --> 54:39.167
- Deep down, you're a coward.
- No.

54:39.333 --> 54:42.917
"Courage consists in staying home,
close to nature,

54:43.083 --> 54:45.292
who is oblivious to our disasters."

54:45.458 --> 54:48.167
Hurry, the tourist boat is about to leave.

54:48.333 --> 54:51.000
Wait, I have an idea.

54:51.167 --> 54:53.750
Give me your lipstick.

55:02.208 --> 55:09.292
"After all, the only interesting thing

55:09.417 --> 55:13.958
is the road that people follow.

55:14.125 --> 55:17.917
The tragic part is that once we know

55:18.083 --> 55:24.875
where they are going, who they are,
everything else is still a mystery."

55:25.042 --> 55:28.542
- Like the scent of eucalyptus.
- Eucalyptus, that's it.

55:28.708 --> 55:35.833
- Too right!
- "And life is an unresolved mystery."

55:36.000 --> 55:39.542
- Hurry up, Paul.
- Shut up, Virginie.

55:49.667 --> 55:52.667
WE ARE DEAD PEOPLE ON LEAVE. AND THE TREES?

56:17.333 --> 56:21.500
TO EARN MONEY, WE DREW FOR THE TOURISTS.

56:21.667 --> 56:24.625
MODERN SLAVES.

56:36.333 --> 56:38.750
Damn these Americans.

56:38.917 --> 56:43.167
It doesn't matter. We'll hit on a different plan.

56:43.375 --> 56:45.500
- All we need to do is...
- What?

56:45.667 --> 56:48.958
We can put on a play.
Maybe they'll give us some dollars.

56:49.125 --> 56:52.417
- What play?
- Something they'll like.

56:52.542 --> 56:55.167
I know. The Vietnam war.

57:51.167 --> 57:55.250
THE NEPHEW OF UNCLE SAM
VERSUS THE NIECE OF UNCLE HO.

58:31.917 --> 58:36.708
A bit of dosh for the actors.

58:36.875 --> 58:38.250
Don't worry, Pierrot.

58:52.333 --> 58:55.292
We've shaken them off. Let's go home.

58:55.458 --> 58:59.000
No, listen, I'm going dancing.

58:59.167 --> 59:01.792
No, come on. You can go tomorrow.

59:01.958 --> 59:05.125
<i>Following chapter. Despair.</i>

59:05.292 --> 59:07.792
- I'm staying here.
- I'll go back alone.

59:07.958 --> 59:10.042
- <i>Hope.</i>
- Yes, you do that.

59:10.208 --> 59:15.375
<i>- Remembrance of things past.
- They told me there was a nightclub.</i>

59:15.542 --> 59:19.958
I'm going dancing. Who cares if we get killed?

59:21.333 --> 59:27.750
Who cares if they find us?
I wanted to buy a record player.

59:27.958 --> 59:31.625
I couldn't, because he keeps buying books.

59:31.792 --> 59:37.417
I don't particularly mind,
but he doesn't even understand that.

59:38.792 --> 59:42.125
I don't care about books, about records.

59:42.292 --> 59:47.917
I don't care about anything, even money.
I just want to live a bit.

59:48.083 --> 59:51.083
<i>But he'll never understand that.</i>

59:52.125 --> 59:54.208
<i>To live.</i>

1:00:10.458 --> 1:00:14.292
I have a very short fate line.

1:00:14.458 --> 1:00:19.042
I have a very short fate line

1:00:19.208 --> 1:00:23.458
So little fate in my hand

1:00:23.625 --> 1:00:27.333
That it scares me for the future

1:00:28.333 --> 1:00:32.333
My fate line, my fate line

1:00:32.542 --> 1:00:36.167
Tell me, darling, what do you think?

1:00:36.333 --> 1:00:39.458
What I think of it? What does it matter?

1:00:39.625 --> 1:00:43.917
I love your hip line, your hip line

1:00:45.292 --> 1:00:49.500
- My fate line!
- I love to caress it

1:00:50.750 --> 1:00:55.083
- Your hip line - My fate line!

1:00:55.250 --> 1:00:58.333
Is a flower in my garden

1:01:12.833 --> 1:01:18.000
